# GenAI Vector Store Project Rules
# These rules help maintain consistency with established project patterns and prevent common issues

## ARCHITECTURE & CODE ORGANIZATION

### Priorities
- Prioritize performance and maintainability
- Reduce DB load and number of queries where possible

### Project Structure Standards
- Follow Go standard project layout strictly
- Place main entry points only in cmd/ subdirectories (cmd/service/, cmd/ops/, cmd/background/)
- Keep core business logic in internal/ packages with clear separation of concerns
- Use internal/ for code that should not be imported by other projects
- Place generated mocks only in mocks/ directory
- Keep API documentation in apidocs/ directory only
- Organize tests by type: unit tests alongside source code, integration tests in src/integTest/
- Use distribution/ only for deployment configurations and build artifacts
- Apply KISS principle - avoid over-engineering
- Avoid fallbacks - fail fast and return error to the client if something goes wrong

### Code Organization Patterns
- Maintain clear separation between service layers: API handlers in cmd/service/api/, middleware in cmd/middleware/, core logic in internal/
- Group related functionality in dedicated internal packages (config, db, embedders, headers, helpers, etc.)
- Follow established API versioning patterns (like v1, v2, ...) when adding new endpoints
- Keep test utilities and common functions in src/integTest/functions/
- Organize integration tests by service area (for example :  endpoints/, emulation_mode/, readonly_mode/, headers/,... etc)

### File Naming and Structure
- Use snake_case for Go file names following project convention
- Add _test.go suffix for all test files
- Use suite_test.go for test suite setup/teardown following Ginkgo patterns
- Name middleware files with descriptive suffixes (e.g., emulation_middleware.go)
- Group related API handlers in appropriately named files

## INTEGRATION TEST STANDARDS

When working with integration tests in src/integTest/:
- Follow the comprehensive testing standards defined in src/integTest/README.md
- These standards cover Ginkgo/BDD naming conventions, test organization, and WireMock patterns
- Always read src/integTest/README.md before creating or modifying integration tests

## CODING STANDARDS

### Go Code Quality
- Add copyright header with current year to ALL new Go files and test files: `// Copyright (c) 2025 Pegasystems Inc.\n// All rights reserved.\n//`, do not modify copyright it if already exist.
- Use structured logging with zap.Logger, never fmt.Print* or log.Print*
- Follow established error handling patterns with proper error wrapping
- Use context.Context for all database and HTTP operations
- Initialize loggers using log.GetNamedLogger() pattern
- Use help function like helpers.GetEnvOrDefault() for environment variable access
- Follow established configuration patterns using internal/config package
- Always create a plan file before making changes.
- Prioritize performance
- Reduce number of queries to database by using bulk queries or SQL functions if that does not add complexity

### Testing Standards
- Use Ginkgo/Gomega BDD framework for integration tests, standard testing package for unit tests
- Place integration test setup in suite_test.go files with BeforeSuite/AfterSuite
- Use established test utilities from src/integTest/functions/
- Follow naming pattern: package_name_test for integration test packages
- Include test coverage and database cleanup in test suites
- Use ExpectNoIdleTransactionsLeft pattern for database tests in every AfterSuite

### Database and API Patterns
- Use pgxpool.Pool for database connections following established patterns
- Use gin.Engine for HTTP routing with established middleware chain
- Use established API response patterns and error handling

## BUILD AND TOOLING

### Approved Tools and Commands
- Use `make` targets defined in Makefile for build operations
- Use `go tool mockery` for generating mocks (never create manual mocks)
- Use `go tool golangci-lint` for linting
- Use `go tool ginkgo` for running integration tests
- Use `./gradle integrationTest` for running integration tests
- Use `go tool staticcheck` for additional static analysis
- Use `make integtest-background` to run background service integration tests only (Use KEEP=XXsec FOCUS="test1|test2.*" for focused specific tests)

### Dependency Management
- Only add dependencies that align with existing technology stack
- Prefer libraries already in use: gin, zap, pgx/v5, ginkgo/gomega, prometheus
- Do not add new HTTP frameworks, logging libraries, or database drivers
- Use established patterns for new dependencies (AWS SDK, GCP SDK patterns already exist)

## ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES DOCUMENTATION

### Documentation Maintenance
- Environment variables documentation is located in `docs/environment-variables.md`
- This file MUST be updated whenever you add, remove, or rename an environment variable
- When modifying environment variables:
  1. Add/update/remove the variable entry in the documentation
  2. Include the variable's description, default value, which services use it, and whether it's required
  3. Update the service-specific usage summary if the change affects service usage
  4. Commit the documentation changes together with your code changes

### Environment Variable Changes Checklist
When working with environment variables, ensure you:
- [ ] Update `docs/environment-variables.md` with the change
- [ ] Document the variable's purpose and impact clearly
- [ ] Specify which services (Service, Ops, Background) use the variable
- [ ] Include default values and example usage
- [ ] Test the change with the new/modified variable
- [ ] Commit documentation and code changes together

## RESTRICTIONS AND ANTI-PATTERNS

### Git Operations Restrictions
- NEVER execute `git commit`, `git push`, or any command that modifies git history
- NEVER create commits or push code to the repository unless the user explicitly requests it
- Only perform read-only git operations (git status, git log, git diff, git show, etc.) without explicit permission
- If the user asks to "save" or "apply" changes, only modify files locally - do NOT commit or push

### File Generation Restrictions
- NEVER create files outside the established project structure
- Generate README files, documentation files, or markdown files only when explicitly asked.
- Do NOT create separate documentation beyond minimal code comments
- Do NOT generate example files or sample configurations

### Code Generation Restrictions  
- Do NOT create new main.go files outside cmd/ subdirectories
- Do NOT generate duplicate middleware or configuration files
- Do NOT generate CLI tools or utilities (pegacloud-cli/ already exists)

### Architecture Violations
- NEVER bypass established middleware patterns
- Do NOT create direct database connections outside internal/db patterns
- Do NOT implement custom logging solutions (use zap)
- Do NOT create new HTTP server patterns (use established gin setup)

## TESTING AND QUALITY REQUIREMENTS

### Test Organization Requirements
- Place ALL integration tests in src/integTest/ with proper package structure
- Use existing test utilities, do NOT create duplicate helper functions
- Follow established environment variable patterns for test configuration
- Maintain test isolation and proper cleanup
- Use established database setup/teardown patterns
- Integration tests log files could be placed in src/integTest/**/logs/<service_name>.logs

### Documentation Requirements
- Add only minimal, necessary code comments
- Do NOT create external documentation files
- Focus on self-documenting code rather than extensive comments
- Use existing swagger/OpenAPI definitions in apidocs/

## WHEN MODIFYING EXISTING CODE

### Refactoring Guidelines
- When moving code, respect established package boundaries when possible
- Maintain existing function signatures when possible
- Preserve established error handling patterns
- Keep existing logging statements and add new ones following zap patterns
- Maintain backward compatibility for internal APIs

### Adding Features
- Follow established API versioning when adding endpoints
- Use existing middleware patterns for new functionality
- Prefer extending existing configuration structures rather than creating new ones if possible
- Add tests following existing patterns and organization
- Use established database migration patterns if schema changes are needed

## ENVIRONMENT AND DEPLOYMENT

### Environment Configuration
- Use established environment variable patterns
- Add new config to internal/config package following existing patterns
- Use helpers package for environment variable access
- Maintain separation between local, AWS, and GCP configurations
- Follow established patterns for secrets management

### Build Integration
- Integrate with existing Makefile targets
- Do NOT create alternative build processes
- Use established Gradle integration for distribution
- Follow existing Docker patterns for containerization
- Maintain compatibility with existing CI/CD processes

## PERFORMANCE TESTING

### K6 Load Testing
- Deploy tests using ./src/perfTest/k6/run-test.sh
- Configure tests via src/perfTest/k6/k6-config.yaml
- Stream K6 logs in real-time during execution

### Load Testing with monitoring and analysis
- Follow the performance test execution guide in src/perfTest/k6/perf-test-with-monitoring-execution-guide.md
- Always create timestamped test directories: load_test_$(date +%Y%m%d_%H%M%S)
- Use the guide's 5-phase approach: Pre-Test Setup, Monitoring Setup, Test Execution, Post-Test Collection, Analysis
- Never modify test artifacts or logs until analysis is complete
- Use src/perfTest/scripts/monitor_service.sh for metrics collection
- Create Python analysis scripts following the guide's templates
